Q#) Write a program that performs arithmetic operations involving different data types (int, double, float)
and observes how Java handles widening conversions automatically.

public class ArithmeticOperations {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Define variables of different data types
        int intValue = 5;
        double doubleValue = 2.5;
        float floatValue = 1.5f;
        
        // Perform arithmetic operations involving different data types
        double result1 = intValue + doubleValue; // int + double, result will be double
        float result2 = floatValue * intValue;   // float * int, result will be float
        double result3 = doubleValue / floatValue; // double / float, result will be double
        
        // Print the results
        System.out.println("Result 1: " + result1); // Widening conversion of int to double
        System.out.println("Result 2: " + result2); // Widening conversion of int to float
        System.out.println("Result 3: " + result3); // Widening conversion of float to double
    }
}
